## Core React Knowledge

### Component Patterns

#### Functional Components (Preferred)
```jsx
// Basic functional component
const MyComponent = ({ prop1, prop2 }) => {
  return <div>{prop1} - {prop2}</div>;
};

// With hooks
const MyStatefulComponent = ({ initialCount }) => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(initialCount);

  return (
    <div>
      Count: {count}
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Increment</button>
    </div>
  );
};
```

#### Class Components (Legacy)
```jsx
class MyClassComponent extends React.Component {
  constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = { count: props.initialCount };
  }

  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        Count: {this.state.count}
        <button onClick={() => this.setState({ count: this.state.count + 1 })}>
          Increment
        </button>
      </div>
    );
  }
}
```

### Essential Hooks

#### useState
```jsx
const [state, setState] = useState(initialState);
// Update options
setState(newValue);
setState(prevState => prevState + 1);
```

#### useEffect
```jsx
// Run on every render
useEffect(() => {
  // Effect code
});

// Run only on mount
useEffect(() => {
  // Effect code
}, []);

// Run when dependencies change
useEffect(() => {
  // Effect code
}, [dependency1, dependency2]);

// Cleanup
useEffect(() => {
  // Effect code
  return () => {
    // Cleanup code
  };
}, [dependencies]);
```

#### useContext
```jsx
const MyContext = React.createContext(defaultValue);

// Provider
<MyContext.Provider value={value}>
  {children}
</MyContext.Provider>

// Consumer (hook)
const value = useContext(MyContext);
```

#### useReducer
```jsx
const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(reducer, initialState);

// Reducer function
function reducer(state, action) {
  switch (action.type) {
    case 'increment':
      return { count: state.count + 1 };
    case 'decrement':
      return { count: state.count - 1 };
    default:
      throw new Error();
  }
}
```

### State Management Approaches

#### Local State
Best for: Component-specific state that doesn't need to be shared widely

#### Context API
Best for: Theme data, authenticated user data, locale preferences, UI state shared across components

#### Redux
Best for: Complex applications with many state transitions, when state is updated in complex ways, when you need robust dev tools, middleware, or want a predictable state container

#### React Query / SWR
Best for: Server state, caching, fetching, and updating data from APIs

### Performance Optimization

#### Memoization
```jsx
// Memoize components
const MemoizedComponent = React.memo(MyComponent);

// Memoize values
const memoizedValue = useMemo(() => computeExpensiveValue(a, b), [a, b]);

// Memoize callbacks
const memoizedCallback = useCallback(() => doSomething(a, b), [a, b]);
```

#### Code Splitting
```jsx
// Dynamic import
const LazyComponent = React.lazy(() => import('./LazyComponent'));

// With Suspense
<Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
  <LazyComponent />
</Suspense>
```

#### Virtualization
For long lists, use react-window or react-virtualized libraries.

### Common Pitfalls

1. Not handling immutability correctly in state updates
2. Missing dependencies in useEffect
3. Creating functions inside render that are passed to child components
4. Not using keys or using index as keys for dynamic lists
5. Mutating props or state directly

